<TITLE> Stocks end lower for third day </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Dec 11 (bdnews24.com)  Dhaka stocks closed lower for a third day Tuesday with banks dominating the turnover board. The market opened steady before rising sharply in the second hour of trading. It however started to decline in the midday session and did not recover at the end. "Whatever happened today, rise or fall was across the board. It seems that the market is behaving normally. Though turnover fell, that does not necessarily mean that something terrible is happening," said Yawar Sayeed, who manages AIMS of Bangladesh. "It may happen as investors especially retail ones have started selling their shares to meet the impending Eid expenses, which is a usual market trend," he said. The DGEN or general index fell 6.69 points or 0.23 percent to close at 2899.55. The DSI or all share price index slumped 7.21 points or 0.29 percent to 2448.25. The DSE-20 blue chip index however rose 1.63 points or 0.07 percent to 2307.70. A total of 226 issues were traded on the bourse with losers beating gainers 126 to 75 and 25 issues holding steady. Turnover on the DSE fell to Tk 960.971 million from Monday's Tk 1 billion from trading of 4,739,066 shares. Exim Bank emerged the top share by value, edging up 1.15 percent to end at Tk 392.75. UCBL followed Exim Bank closing at Tk 4611.50, down 4.29 percent. NBL increased 2.43 percent to close at Tk 1282.50. BRAC Bank, one of the most active shares, rose after falling on Monday, ending up 0.19 percent to Tk 1528.50. BOC Bangladesh closed 4.04 percent down at Tk 308.70. Among the other top shares by value, Summit Power, Islami Bank Perpetual Bond, Square Pharma and ACI declined. Dutch Bangla Bank rose after it said it had decided to increase the authorised capital to Tk 4000 million from Tk 400 million subject to the approval of Bangladesh Bank. Aramit, Meghna Pet Industries, Quasem Silk, Legacy Footwear and BD Dyeing were among the major gainers. ICB, Reliance Insurance, Federal Insurance, Fine Foods Limited and Reckitt Benckiser led the losers. All the indices on the Chittagong Stock Exchange ended down. The CSCX or CSE selective categories index slipped 27.99 points or 0.58 percent to 4724.47. The CASPI or all share price index ended at 7393.79, down 50.03 points or 0.67 percent. The CSE-30 blue chip index dipped 11.46 points or 0.17 percent to end at 6496.35. Turnover on the bourse stood at Tk 125.028 million from Monday's Tk 137.605 million. A total of 1,100,387 shares were traded with 17 issues advancing, 93 declining and seven remaining unchanged. bd
